6","1387":"1387","about 1423":"circa 1423","3Sep. 1428":"3 september 1428","1428":"1428","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1368–3Sep. 1428":"1368–3 September 1428","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1387–1476":"1387–1476","1423–1486":"1423–1486","1344–1398":"1344–1398","1347–1415":"1347–1415","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1423":"1423","1344":"1344","1476":"1476","1398":"1398","1486":"1486","1387":"1387","about 1423":"about 1423","3Sep. 1428":"3 September 1428","1428":"1428","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ashton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places so called, especially Ashton-under-Lyne near Manchester. Most are named from Old English <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’; the one in Northamptonshire is <i>(æt thǣm) æscum</i> ‘(at the) ash trees’. Others have been assimilated to this from different sources. The one in Devon is ‘the settlement (<i>tūn</i>) of Æschere’, while the one in Hertfordshire is ‘the settlement of Ælli’."],"variants":[{"name":"Aspden","meanings":["English: habitational name from Aspden (alias Aspen) in Oswaldtwistle, Lancashire. This surname has been confused with   Ashton   and   Austin  , and probably also with   Aston   and   Astin  , all of which are common surnames in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John IV Ashton , Knight was born in 1368, his father, Sir John III de Ashton , Lord, Knight, Military Commander, MP, was 24 and his mother, Alice Standish, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Byron. He died on 3 September 1428, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1368–3Sep. 1428":"1368–3. september 1428","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1387–1476":"1387–1476","1423–1486":"1423–1486","1344–1398":"1344–1398","1347–1415":"1347–1415","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1423":"1423","1344":"1344","1476":"1476","1398":"1398","1486":"1486","1387":"1387","about 1423":"umbes 1423","3Sep. 1428":"3. september 1428","1428":"1428","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1368–3Sep. 1428":"1368–3. syyskuuta 1428","1368–1428":"1368–1428","1387–1476":"1387–1476","1423–1486":"1423–1486","1344–1398":"1344–1398","1347–1415":"1347–1415","1415":"1415","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1423":"1423","1344":"1344","1476":"1476","1398":"1398","1486":"1486","1387":"1387","about 1423":"noin 1423","3Sep. 1428":"3. syyskuu